WEBVTT

00:00:01.200 --> 00:00:03.280
<v Teacher>What was the word for <i>what</i>?

00:00:04.800 --> 00:00:05.360
<v Student><b>Qué.</b>

00:00:05.920 --> 00:00:09.040
<v Teacher>And do you remember how was <i>to pass</i>?

00:00:09.500 --> 00:00:11.420
<v Student><b>Pasar.</b>

00:00:11.420 --> 00:00:16.780
<v Teacher><b>Pasar.</b> And this can also mean like <i>to happen</i>. <i>To pass</i> in the sense of <i>to occur</i>.

00:00:16.780 --> 00:00:19.420
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>he passes</i>?

00:00:20.560 --> 00:00:21.440
<v Student><b>Pasa.</b>

00:00:21.440 --> 00:00:21.760
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:21.760 --> 00:00:24.400
<v Teacher>And <i>she passes</i>:

00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:25.200
<v Student><b>Pasa.</b>

00:00:25.200 --> 00:00:26.400
<v Teacher>And <i>it passes</i>:

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:27.120
<v Student><b>Pasa.</b>

00:00:27.120 --> 00:00:27.520
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:27.520 --> 00:00:33.280
<v Teacher>And if you want to say <i>what passes</i>, meaning <i>what happens</i>, <i>what's going on</i>, <i>what is happening?</i>:

00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:36.080
<v Student>I remembered it now.

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:40.480
<v Student>I went through the whole process and I remember people saying ¿<b>qué pasó?</b>

00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:42.160
<v Teacher>This is the past.

00:00:42.140 --> 00:00:51.340
<v Teacher>We said that when you emphasize that <i>-o</i> on the end it's actually the version for <i>he/she/it</i> in the past, so ¿<b>qué pasó?</b> is <i>what happened?</i>,

00:00:51.340 --> 00:00:52.780
<v Teacher>and we will look at this later.

00:00:52.780 --> 00:00:54.540
<v Teacher>But what is <i>what's happening</i>?

00:00:54.540 --> 00:00:56.860
<v Teacher><i>What is happening?</i>:

00:00:57.500 --> 00:00:58.140
<v Student>¿<b>Qué pasa?</b>

00:00:58.140 --> 00:00:58.940
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:58.940 --> 00:01:04.940
<v Teacher>So if you want to say <i>I want to know what's going on</i>, <i>I want to know what's happening</i>, <i>I want to know what's passing</i>:

00:01:05.659 --> 00:01:08.380
<v Student><b>Quiero saber qué pasa.</b>

00:01:08.619 --> 00:01:10.060
<v Teacher><b>Quiero saber qué pasa.</b>

00:01:10.219 --> 00:01:12.619
<v Teacher><i>I want to know what's happening.</i>

00:01:12.660 --> 00:01:13.380
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:13.380 --> 00:01:23.940
<v Teacher>There's one more thing we need to know about the present, and it's gonna fill in, happily, a grey area for us which you might be wondering already: how did we get <b>tiene</b>

00:01:24.580 --> 00:01:33.540
<v Teacher><i>he/she/it/you</i> (formal) <i>has</i> or <i>have</i>, and then the other versions <b>tienen</b>, <b>tienes</b>, from <b>tener</b>?

00:01:33.540 --> 00:01:35.780
<v Teacher><i>To want</i> is <b>querer</b>.

00:01:35.780 --> 00:01:37.460
<v Teacher>What is <i>I want</i>?

00:01:37.980 --> 00:01:38.860
<v Student><b>Quiero.</b>

00:01:38.860 --> 00:01:39.820
<v Teacher>Quiero.

00:01:39.820 --> 00:01:43.020
<v Teacher>So how does querer become quiero?

00:01:43.340 --> 00:01:46.860
<v Teacher>So there's something else we need to know about the present to understand this,

00:01:46.860 --> 00:01:49.820
<v Teacher>and then we can manage the present completely.

00:01:49.720 --> 00:02:00.520
<v Teacher>So what's happening is that when we have an <i>e</i> in the “to” form of the verb like in <b>tener</b>: <i>to have</i>, like in <b>querer</b>: <i>to want</i>;

00:02:00.140 --> 00:02:12.540
<v Teacher>when we have an <i>e</i> inside of the verb it's part of the root, not part of the ending. Not that <i>-er</i>, that doesn't count. But the /<i>e</i>/ in <i>ten-</i> and the /<i>e</i>/ in <i>quer-</i> of

00:02:13.340 --> 00:02:26.700
<v Teacher>When we stress it, when we emphasize it, it often splits; most of the time, it splits into an <i>ie</i> under the stress of that accent,

00:02:26.720 --> 00:02:32.159
<v Teacher>under the stress when we say <b>querer</b> we have the accent on the end, we have the accent on the ending.

00:02:32.159 --> 00:02:41.280
<v Teacher>Then when we take off that <i>-er</i> we put -<i>o</i>, we would have <b>quero</b> but when we stress down that <i>e</i> it splits and it becomes <b>quiero</b>.

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:42.840
<v Teacher>The same for <b>tener</b>:

00:02:42.840 --> 00:02:52.120
<v Teacher>we would have <b>tene</b> for <i>he has</i>, but when we stress down on that <i>e</i> it splits and it becomes <b>tiene</b>.

00:02:51.960 --> 00:02:53.480
<v Teacher>The same for <i>come</i>.

00:02:53.480 --> 00:03:03.960
<v Teacher>We have <b>venir</b>. But when we say <i>he comes, she comes, it comes</i>, <i>you</i> (formal) <i>come</i>, it would be <b>vene</b>, but it becomes <b>viene</b>.

00:03:03.500 --> 00:03:08.540
<v Teacher>Now it's not happening with <b>tengo</b>, <b>vengo</b>, because we can say the <i>n</i> and the <i>g</i> kind of hold it up.

00:03:08.540 --> 00:03:10.940
<v Teacher>So this is probably why it got saved.

00:03:10.940 --> 00:03:12.620
<v Teacher>But otherwise it splits.

00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:23.040
<v Teacher>Now, this might seem quite an abstract thing to get your head around, but what is very helpful is that we have these between words in English and Spanish.

00:03:22.840 --> 00:03:26.440
<v Teacher>We can identify these between words in English and Spanish.

00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:34.040
<v Teacher>For example, we have a word that we use for time in English, but only in music.

00:03:33.760 --> 00:03:35.600
<v Teacher>Do you know what is this word?

00:03:35.600 --> 00:03:37.920
<v Teacher>A word we use for time but only in music.

00:03:37.920 --> 00:03:41.440
<v Teacher>When you speak about the time, the rhythm of music, you talk about its:

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:42.720
<v Student><i>Beat</i>.

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:45.520
<v Teacher>Not <i>beat</i> but <i>tempo</i>.

00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:49.360
<v Teacher>Now, <i>time</i> in Spanish is <b>tiempo</b>.

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:55.040
<v Teacher>You see the difference between <i>tempo</i> and <b>tiempo</b>, other than the Spanish pronunciation,

00:03:55.060 --> 00:03:57.620
<v Teacher>is that the <i>e</i> has split into <i>ie</i>.

00:03:57.620 --> 00:04:01.700
<v Teacher>So you can even see it between words in English and Spanish.

00:04:01.780 --> 00:04:03.860
<v Teacher><i>Concert</i> in Spanish

00:04:03.860 --> 00:04:07.379
<v Teacher>is - try and do the same thing.

00:04:07.940 --> 00:04:09.060
<v Student><b>Concierto.</b>

00:04:09.060 --> 00:04:10.020
<v Teacher><b>Concierto.</b> Good.

00:04:10.020 --> 00:04:12.900
<v Teacher>You stuck in an <i>o</i> to make it sound more Spanish and you split that <i>e</i>.

00:04:12.900 --> 00:04:13.860
<v Teacher><b>Concierto</b>.

00:04:13.860 --> 00:04:16.500
<v Teacher><i>November</i> is <b>Noviembre</b>.

00:04:16.500 --> 00:04:18.660
<v Teacher>So this will help us remember.

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:20.720
<v Teacher>So this happens most of the time.

00:04:20.720 --> 00:04:22.639
<v Teacher>We already saw places that it doesn't happen;

00:04:22.639 --> 00:04:28.080
<v Teacher>we saw very briefly the verb <b>llegar</b>, which was <i>to arrive</i> and we said <b>llego</b>, <i>I arrive</i>.

00:04:28.080 --> 00:04:31.520
<v Teacher>We saw <b>esperar</b>, which was <i>to wait</i> or <i>to hope</i>,

00:04:31.240 --> 00:04:32.280
<v Teacher><b>espero</b>.

00:04:32.520 --> 00:04:33.480
<v Teacher>It's not happening.

00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:35.640
<v Teacher>But most of the time it's going to happen.

00:04:35.640 --> 00:04:43.320
<v Teacher>We saw it happening with <b>tener</b> which became <b>tiene</b>, <i>he/she/it/you</i> (formal), <b>tienen</b>, <i>they</i> or <i>you</i> (plural),

00:04:43.320 --> 00:04:45.960
<v Teacher><b>tienes</b>, <i>you</i> (informal).

00:04:45.400 --> 00:04:51.080
<v Teacher>We saw it happening with <b>venir</b>, <i>to come</i>: <b>viene</b>, <b>vienes</b>, <b>vienen</b>.

00:04:51.080 --> 00:04:53.720
<v Teacher>Another verb that we see this way is <b>pensar</b>.

00:04:53.720 --> 00:04:56.040
<v Teacher>What do you think <b>pensar</b> means?

00:04:56.800 --> 00:04:57.840
<v Student><i>Thoughtful</i>.

00:04:57.840 --> 00:04:58.640
<v Teacher>But it is a verb.

00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:00.640
<v Teacher>There is no verb <i>to thoughtful</i>, is there?


00:05:02.800 --> 00:05:03.920
<v Student>Well, <i>to think</i>.

00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:06.000
<v Teacher>Yes, that's it, <i>to think</i>.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:09.920
<v Teacher>It's very useful for us to group words into families. So "verb" is a family.


00:05:09.920 --> 00:05:18.240
<v Teacher>So when you decide what type of word it is, then you narrow down the possible behaviors

00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:21.560
<v Teacher>of that word, and you manage to manage it much easier.

00:05:21.560 --> 00:05:27.000
<v Teacher>And making that very clearly - that connection - is really really helpful for you. <i>To think</i>, <b>pensar</b>.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:30.680
<v Teacher>So if you say <i>I think</i>, how is it going to be?

00:05:31.540 --> 00:05:32.580
<v Student><b>Pienso.</b>

00:05:32.580 --> 00:05:33.220
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:40.020
<v Teacher>It would be <b>penso</b> but you stress down on that <i>e</i> and it splits into <i>ie</i> and you get <b>pienso</b>.

00:05:41.420 --> 00:05:48.460
<v Teacher>How is <i>he thinks</i> or <i>she thinks</i> or <i>it thinks</i> or <i>you</i> (formal)?

00:05:48.460 --> 00:05:49.600
<v Student><b>Piense.</b>

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:50.700
<v Teacher>This sounds like vowel harmony.

00:05:50.760 --> 00:05:57.320
<v Teacher>I mean it sounds nice, <b>piense</b>, because we have <i>ie</i> and then we want to put an <i>e</i> next to it because it matches.

00:05:57.320 --> 00:05:59.240
<v Teacher>But that's Turkish grammar.

00:05:59.740 --> 00:06:04.300
<v Teacher>You must know where you are with any verb. And to know where you are you must go back to the “to" form.

00:06:04.300 --> 00:06:05.020
<v Teacher>Then you are confident.

00:06:05.020 --> 00:06:06.620
<v Student>So it's <b>piensar</b>.

00:06:06.620 --> 00:06:07.340
<v Teacher><b>Pensar.</b>

00:06:07.340 --> 00:06:08.380
<v Student><b>Pensar</b>,

00:06:07.960 --> 00:06:09.080
<v Student>not <b>penser</b>.

00:06:09.080 --> 00:06:10.120
<v Teacher>No, <b>pensar</b>.

00:06:10.120 --> 00:06:12.440
<v Teacher>So you must go back there and then you feel confident.

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:17.159
<v Teacher>Otherwise the base is going to effect what vowel you want to put on.

00:06:17.159 --> 00:06:18.120
<v Student><b>Piensa.</b>

00:06:18.120 --> 00:06:19.319
<v Teacher><b>Piensa.</b>

00:06:19.319 --> 00:06:20.919
<v Teacher>You (informal):

00:06:21.980 --> 00:06:22.940
<v Student><b>Piensas.</b>

00:06:22.940 --> 00:06:23.260
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:23.260 --> 00:06:25.500
<v Teacher><i>What do you think?</i>:

00:06:25.820 --> 00:06:27.020
<v Student>¿<b>Qué piensas?</b>

00:06:27.020 --> 00:06:28.540
<v Teacher>Yeah. ¿<b>Qué piensas?</b>

00:06:28.700 --> 00:06:35.820
<v Teacher>This is a useful verb as well actually. Because if you say <i>I think to eat</i> it means <i>I plan on eating</i>.

00:06:35.520 --> 00:06:37.440
<v Teacher>You can say <i>I think to eat</i>,

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:38.320
<v Teacher>that simple.

00:06:38.320 --> 00:06:39.360
<v Teacher><i>I think to eat</i>:

00:06:39.360 --> 00:06:40.800
<v Teacher>how would it sound?

00:06:41.840 --> 00:06:43.440
<v Student><b>Pienso comer.</b>

00:06:43.440 --> 00:06:44.320
<v Teacher><b>Pienso comer.</b>

00:06:44.740 --> 00:06:48.180
<v Teacher><i>I think to eat later</i> is <i>I plan on eating later</i>.

00:06:48.180 --> 00:06:50.740
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>I plan on eating later</i>?

00:06:51.540 --> 00:06:54.260
<v Student><b>Pienso comer tarde.</b>

00:06:54.260 --> 00:06:57.460
<v Teacher>That means <i>I plan on eating late</i>,

00:06:57.139 --> 00:07:04.020
<v Teacher>which is fine, but <i>later</i> is <i>more late</i>. And <i>more</i> is related to <i>massive</i>.

00:07:04.020 --> 00:07:05.060
<v Student><b>Más tarde.</b>

00:07:05.060 --> 00:07:05.460
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:05.460 --> 00:07:07.060
<v Teacher><b>Pienso comer más tarde.</b>

00:07:07.139 --> 00:07:08.500
<v Teacher><i>I plan on eating later.</i>

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:10.660
<v Teacher>So you can use it like that as well.

00:07:10.360 --> 00:07:14.280
<v Teacher>We saw <b>venir</b> also splits with the exception of <b>vengo</b>.

00:07:14.280 --> 00:07:18.360
<v Teacher><i>He comes, she comes, you</i> (formal) - how would that be?

00:07:18.680 --> 00:07:19.480
<v Student><b>Viene.</b>

00:07:19.480 --> 00:07:20.360
<v Teacher><b>Viene.</b>

00:07:20.360 --> 00:07:20.760
<v Teacher><i>They</i>:

00:07:22.240 --> 00:07:22.960
<v Student><b>Vienen.</b>

00:07:23.120 --> 00:07:24.000
<v Teacher><b>Vienen.</b>

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.400
<v Teacher><i>You</i> (informal):

00:07:26.400 --> 00:07:27.280
<v Student><b>Vienes.</b>

00:07:27.280 --> 00:07:27.600
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:29.520
<v Teacher>Do you remember how was <i>when</i>?

00:07:29.840 --> 00:07:30.800
<v Student><b>Cuándo.</b>

00:07:30.800 --> 00:07:31.760
<v Teacher><b>Cuándo.</b>

00:07:31.760 --> 00:07:33.520
<v Teacher><i>When are you coming?</i>:

00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:35.680
<v Student>¿<b>Cuándo vienes?</b>

00:07:35.680 --> 00:07:37.520
<v Teacher>¿<b>Cuándo vienes?</b>

00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:41.760
<v Teacher><b>Entender</b> means <i>to understand</i>.

00:07:41.460 --> 00:07:46.580
<v Teacher>You can use <b>comprender</b> if you forget it, but <b>entender</b> is better. It's more common.

00:07:46.580 --> 00:07:50.419
<v Teacher>But <b>comprender</b> is easier because it sounds like <i>comprehend</i>,

00:07:50.419 --> 00:07:53.460
<v Teacher>and also in <b>comprender</b> the <i>e</i> doesn't split.

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:56.320
<v Teacher><i>I understand</i> is <b>comprendo</b>.

00:07:56.320 --> 00:07:59.520
<v Teacher>But with <b>entender</b> it does split.

00:07:59.520 --> 00:08:01.280
<v Teacher>So you can use <b>comprender</b>,

00:08:01.860 --> 00:08:05.620
<v Teacher>but most common in Spanish is <b>entender</b> for understand.

00:08:05.620 --> 00:08:07.380
<v Teacher>And here the <i>e</i> does split.

00:08:07.380 --> 00:08:09.780
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>I understand</i>?

00:08:10.080 --> 00:08:11.080
<v Student><b>Entiendo.</b>

00:08:11.080 --> 00:08:12.080
<v Teacher><b>Entiendo.</b>

00:08:14.080 --> 00:08:18.560
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>he understands</i>?

00:08:18.560 --> 00:08:20.560
<v Student><b>Entiende.</b>

00:08:20.560 --> 00:08:21.280
<v Teacher><b>Entiende.</b> Good. <i>They</i>:

00:08:22.560 --> 00:08:23.760
<v Student><b>Entienden.</b>

00:08:23.760 --> 00:08:25.040
<v Teacher><b>Entienden.</b>

00:08:25.040 --> 00:08:28.640
<v Teacher><b>Perder</b> means <i>to lose</i>.

00:08:28.640 --> 00:08:31.680
<v Teacher>It's kind of related to <i>perish</i>,

00:08:31.740 --> 00:08:39.659
<v Teacher>there is a connection there, or perishable food. You know, food that rots, or real food. Perder, to lose.

00:08:39.659 --> 00:08:40.780
<v Teacher><i>I lose</i>:

00:08:41.840 --> 00:08:42.880
<v Student><b>Pierdo.</b>

00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:43.520
<v Teacher><b>Pierdo.</b>

00:08:43.520 --> 00:08:43.840
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:45.440
<v Teacher>The process is <b>perder</b>-<b>perdo</b>, maybe it splits: <b>pierdo</b>.

00:08:45.440 --> 00:08:47.280
<v Teacher>Good. <i>I lose it</i>:

00:08:47.280 --> 00:08:48.320
<v Student><b>Lo pierdo.</b>

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:48.960
<v Teacher><b>Lo pierdo.</b> Good.

00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:50.720
<v Teacher><i>I lose them</i>:

00:08:51.300 --> 00:08:52.500
<v Student><b>Los pierdo.</b>

00:08:52.500 --> 00:08:53.620
<v Teacher><b>Los pierdo.</b> Good.
